article.headline: Penn State sets home attendance record
article.linkText: 15,389 watch No. 8 Penn State beat Michigan
article.story:
STATE COLLEGE, Pa. (AP) -- Jess Strom had just her second career
double-double against Michigan. But her defense set the tone for
Penn State's win.

Strom had 10 points and 12 assists to help No. 8 Penn State beat
the Wolverines 73-44 Sunday. She had two of her game-high four
steals in the first 3{ minutes, and the Lady Lions (19-4, 11-1 Big
Ten) jumped out to an early and insurmountable lead in front of a
record crowd.

"It helped out a lot that I could just help where I needed
to," Strom said. "We came out, got a couple of steals early, and
it just built. We just kept running."

Penn State opened with a 13-0 run, while the Wolverines (11-15,
4-9) committed five turnovers and missed their first five shots.

"When you start the game turning it over four straight times
against a very good team and give up incredibly easy layups, it's
then very hard to play from behind," Michigan coach Cheryl Burnett
said.

Tanisha Wright had three layups in another 13-3 run that made it
26-6 midway through the first half. By halftime, Penn State led
38-15 and that was the closest Michigan got the rest of the game.

"Tonight, we came out and played gangbusters," Penn State
coach Rene Portland said. "We fed off a number of things --
certainly played off the crowd, fed off each other. Our defense was
really terrific in the beginning. Jess was able to back off their
point guard and make a lot of things happen."

Kelly Mazzante led the Lady Lions with 16 points, Wright scored
14, and Jessica Brungo and Jennifer Harris each scored 10.

Jennifer Smith led Michigan with 22 points and 10 rebounds, and
Niki Reams scored 10.

The attendance of 15,389 was a Penn State home record. It was
just the second sold out home game in Penn State women's basketball
history, and the first since the 15,261-seat Bryce Jordan Center
opened in 1996.

"We sat back and watched a great team play a great game today
and as the opposing coach, I just feel badly that we couldn't be
more competitive in such an incredible environment," Burnett said.

The only previous sellout was Feb. 6, 1994, when the top-ranked
Lady Lions faced No. 8 Iowa in the 7,264-seat Rec Hall. Penn
State's previous home attendance record was 13,305 set Jan. 18
against Illinois.
